  "answer": "**The term \"bhukti\" does not appear to be explicitly defined as \"worldly enjoyment\" (in the sense of sensual or material pleasures) within the Smṛti or Dharmaśāstra texts available in the Falsafa corpus.** \n\nThe sole occurrence of \"bhukti\" is in the *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, where it refers to legal **possession** or usufruct (the right to enjoy the fruits/use of property) in a dispute over a deposited pledge: \"When two men dispute over a pledge deposited with them, He who has possession (*bhukti*) has the fruit of it, provided it was not taken by force.\"[^1] This usage aligns with classical Dharmashāstra discussions of property rights rather than general worldly pleasures.\n\nRelated terms like *bhoga* (enjoyment or consumption) appear occasionally but in narrower senses:\n- In the *Vṛhaspatitattva*, *bhoga* denotes \"all that is eaten and drunk,\" *upabhoga* what is worn as adornment, and *paribhoga* having a spouse/servants; together, these constitute *aiśvarya* (lordship/wealth).[^2]\n- In the *Vīramitrodaya*, *bhoga* refers to astronomical \"passage,\" unrelated to enjoyment.[^3]\n\nNo passages discuss \"bhukti\" (or directly equivalent concepts) as worldly enjoyment permitted within *dharma*—such as for the householder (*gṛhastha*) stage, where regulated pursuit of *kāma* (pleasure) and *artha* (wealth) is typically allowed alongside *dharma*. The corpus lacks explicit treatment of this topic under these terms. Broader Smṛti texts like *Manusmṛti* address householder duties involving rites and purification but not \"bhukti\" or worldly enjoyment by that name.[^4]\n\nIf \"bhukti\" refers to a specific traditional interpretation (e.g., fruition of karma in Mīmāṃsā or yoga contexts), it is not substantiated here. The corpus covers only 37 works, with limited Smṛti/Dharmashāstra representation.\n\n[^1]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 5, p-57dada](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/05/translation/#p-57dada).\n[^2]: *Vṛhaspatitattva*, [Chapter 1, p-cce0c6](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-cce0c6).\n[^3]: *Vīramitrodaya*, [Chapter 1, p-d42af4](/works/unknown-viramitrodaya-d4b632/01/translation/#p-d42af4).\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapters 4 & 6 (householder rites/purification; no \"bhukti\"). E.g., [Chapter 4, p-7a3359](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-7a3359); [Chapter 6, p-89d810](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/#p-89d810).",
